content.thinking:
This is the canonical example of how to wire picorv32's mem_* interface to a memory. This is perfect for the practice task. The key pattern:

```verilog
always @(posedge clk) begin
    mem_ready <= 0;
    if (mem_valid && !mem_ready) begin
        if (mem_addr < 1024) begin
            mem_ready <= 1;
            mem_rdata <= memory[mem_addr >> 2];
            if (mem_wstrb[0]) memory[mem_addr >> 2][ 7: 0] <= mem_wdata[ 7: 0];
            if (mem_wstrb[1]) memory[mem_addr >> 2][15: 8] <= mem_wdata[15: 8];
            if (mem_wstrb[2]) memory[mem_addr >> 2][23:16] <= mem_wdata[23:16];
            if (mem_wstrb[3]) memory[mem_addr >> 2][31:24] <= mem_wdata[31:24];
        end
    end
end
```

Note the 2-cycle handshake: when mem_valid is seen and mem_ready not yet asserted, it takes one cycle to respond. The mem_ready is registered (one cycle delay). This is the "wait cycle" version.

Now let me look at how the look-ahead interface can be used for single-cycle response. Let me search the codebase for an example that uses mem_la_* signals. The picosoc.v might use them.

